    "message_1": "A student gathered data on the population of a city from the past 5 years. Using Lagrange interpolation, find the estimated population of the city in year 2023 if the population in 2018 was 500,000 and the following data was collected:\n\nYear| Population\n---|---\n2019| 540,000\n2020| 580,000\n2021| 620,000\n2022| 660,000",
    "message_2": "To estimate the population of the city in 2023 using Lagrange interpolation, we will use the given data points (2018, 500,000), (2019, 540,000), (2020, 580,000), (2021, 620,000), and (2022, 660,000). The formula for Lagrange interpolation is:\n\nP(x) = L0(x) * f(x0) + L1(x) * f(x1) + L2(x) * f(x2) + L3(x) * f(x3) + L4(x) * f(x4)\n\nwhere\nP(x) is the estimated population at year x,\nLk(x) are the Lagrange basis polynomials,\nf(xk) are the known population values at the given years,\nand x0, x1, x2, x3, and x4 are the given years (2018, 2019, 2020, 2021, and 2022).\n\nFirst, we need to find the Lagrange basis polynomials Lk(x) for k = 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4:\n\nL0(x) = ((x - x1)(x - x2)(x - x3)(x - x4)) / ((x0 - x1)(x0 - x2)(x0 - x3)(x0 - x4))\nL1(x) = ((x - x0)(x - x2)(x - x3)(x - x4)) / ((x1 - x0)(x1 - x2)(x1 - x3)(x1 - x4))\nL2(x) = ((x - x0)(x - x1)(x - x3)(x - x4)) / ((x2 - x0)(x2 - x1)(x2 - x3)(x2 - x4))\nL3(x) = ((x - x0)(x - x1)(x - x2)(x - x4)) / ((x3 - x0)(x3 - x1)(x3 - x2)(x3 - x4))\nL4(x) = ((x - x0)(x - x1)(x - x2)(x - x3)) / ((x4 - x0)(x4 - x1)(x4 - x2)(x4 - x3))\n\nNow, we will plug in the given data points and the year 2023 into the formula:\n\nP(2023) = L0(2023) * 500,000 + L1(2023) * 540,000 + L2(2023) * 580,000 + L3(2023) * 620,000 + L4(2023) * 660,000\n\nCalculating the Lagrange basis polynomials for x = 2023:\n\nL0(2023) = ((2023 - 2019)(2023 - 2020)(2023 - 2021)(2023 - 2022)) / ((2018 - 2019)(2018 - 2020)(2018 - 2021)(2018 - 2022)) = (4 * 3 * 2 * 1) / (-1 * -2 * -3 * -4) = 1/6\nL1(2023) = ((2023 - 2018)(2023 - 2020)(2023 - 2021)(2023 - 2022)) / ((2019 - 2018)(2019 - 2020)(2019 - 2021)(2019 - 2022)) = (5 * 3 * 2 * 1) / (1 * -1 * -2 * -3) = 5/6\nL2(2023) = ((2023 - 2018)(2023 - 2019)(2023 - 2021)(2023 - 2022)) / ((2020 - 2018)(2020 - 2019)(2020 - 2021)(2020 - 2022)) = (5 * 4 * 2 * 1) / (2 * 1 * -1 * -2) = 10/4 = 5/2\nL3(2023) = ((2023 - 2018)(2023 - 2019)(2023 - 2020)(2023 - 2022)) / ((2021 - 2018)(2021 - 2019)(2021 - 2020)(2021 - 2022)) = (5 * 4 * 3 * 1) / (3 * 2 * 1 * -1) = -60/6 = -10\nL4(2023) = ((2023 - 2018)(2023 - 2019)(2023 - 2020)(2023 - 2021)) / ((2022 - 2018)(2022 - 2019)(2022 - 2020)(2022 - 2021)) = (5 * 4 * 3 * 2) / (4 * 3 * 2 * 1) = 5\n\nNow, we will plug these values into the formula:\n\nP(2023) = (1/6) * 500,000 + (5/6) * 540,000 + (5/2) * 580,000 + (-10) * 620,000 + 5 * 660,000\nP(2023) = 83,333.33 + 450,000 + 1,450,000 - 6,200,000 + 3,300,000\nP(2023) = 700,000\n\nSo, the estimated population of the city in 2023 using Lagrange interpolation is 700,000."
